It is well known that many factors and practices related
to cultivation can improve the growth and EO quality of
many aromatic plants [11]. Among these practices, application
of mineral and biological fertilizers, such as N, P, and K
amendments and mycorrhizal inoculation have been recom-
mended [12, 13]. In fact, the use of these cultural practices has
many advantages, which include promoting the physical and
biological properties of soil [14], stimulating plant growth and
biomass yield through improving nutrient uptake [15], and
enhancing the content and quality of EOs via modulation of
the levels of enzymes that participate in the biosynthesis of
volatile terpenes [16].
